<% title "Reimbursements for #{@event.name}" %>
<% page_md %>
<%= render 'events/nav' %>

<h1 class="heading">
  Reimbursements
  <%= link_to 'https://app.expensify.com/', class: 'btn', target: '_blank' do %>
    <%= inline_icon 'external' %>
    Open Expensify
  <% end %>
</h1>

<div class="mb4">
  <p>
    Hack Club Bank currently uses a service called
    <a class="info" href="https://www.expensify.com" target="_blank">Expensify</a>
    to streamline your reimbursement process. Expensify allows
    you to upload receipts and receive reimbursements back
    into their bank account üè¶.
  </p>

  <p>
    Get in touch with your point of contact
    <strong><%= @event.point_of_contact.full_name %></strong> at
    <% if organizer_signed_in? %>
      <%= mail_to @event.point_of_contact.email, nil, class: 'inline' %>
    <% else %>
      <span class="muted">(sign in to view)</span>
    <% end%>
    with the email of the person to be reimbursed, and they'll be invited
    to Expensify to upload their receipts.
  </p>
</div>

<h2 class="mb2">Expensify FAQ</h2>

<ul class="list-reset">
  <li class="mb3">
    <details open>
      <summary class="inline-block cursor-pointer">
        <strong>What happens when someone's invited to Expensify?</strong>
      </summary>
      <article>
        <p>
        We'll invite whoever needs to be reimbursed (let's call them "Max") to Expensify through their email.
        When Max receives the email, they'll make an account or log into Expensify, where they can upload their
        receipts as "expenses," and submit their expenses in a "Report."
        </p>
        <p>
        When Max submits a report, your point of contact will receive it, make sure that the numbers make sense,
        and approve the reimbursement. Max will get a couple of emails letting them know that the expense was approved,
        and the reimbursement is on their way.
        </p>
        <p>
        To receive the reimbursement, Max will need to connect their bank account with Expensify. They'll need to do it
        only once, and for future reimbursements, the funds will arrive into their bank account within a few days.
        </p>
      </article>
    </details>
  </li>

  <li class="mb3">
    <details>
      <summary class="inline-block cursor-pointer">
        <strong>Can I just send them a check or direct deposit?</strong>
      </summary>
      <article>
        <p>
        Usually, no. We ask that you make all reimbursements through Expensify on Hack Club Bank, because Expensify makes it
        easy for us as a nonprofit to keep track of receipts and expenses in an auditable way.
        </p>
        <p>
        If you think you have an exceptional case where using Expensify isn't sensible, feel free to get in touch with
        your point of contact!
        </p>
      </article>
    </details>
  </li>

  <li class="mb3">
    <details>
      <summary class="inline-block cursor-pointer">
        <strong>Does the reimbursement come out of my account balance, or my card balance?</strong>
      </summary>
      <article>
        <p>
        Reimbursements from Expensify draw money from your account balance, where you currently have
        <strong><%= render_money @event.balance %></strong>.
        </p>
      </article>
    </details>
  </li>

  <li class="mb3">
    <details>
      <summary class="inline-block cursor-pointer">
        <strong>How long does it take to be reimbursed?</strong>
      </summary>
      <article>
        <p>
        If the reimbursee has a bank account connected to Expensify, they'll receive the reimbursement within a few days of
        its approval. If they need to connect their bank account to Expensify, that may take a couple of extra days at most.
        </p>
      </article>
    </details>
  </li>

  <li class="mb3">
    <details>
      <summary class="inline-block cursor-pointer">
        <strong>Can I reimburse someone for a part of an expense?</strong>
      </summary>
      <article>
        <p>
        Yep! When you submit your receipts to get reimbursed on Expensify, just make sure to make the expense amount the
        partial reimbursement amount rather than the full expense, and add a note there that it's a partial reimbursement.
        </p>
      </article>
    </details>
  </li>
</ul>

